      { type: "h1", text: `[Title Page]\nWhy Great Manufacturers Stay Invisible\nHow to Turn a Good Manufacturing Business into a Recognised Brand\nBy [Your Name/Author Name]` },
      { type: "p", text: `Copyright © 2026 by Sudharsan K R\nAll rights reserved.\nNo part of this publication may be reproduced, distributed, or transmitted in any form or by any means—including photocopying, recording, or other electronic or mechanical methods—without the prior written permission of the author, except in the case of brief quotations embodied in critical reviews and certain other non-commercial uses permitted by copyright law.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Disclaimer: This book is designed to provide accurate and authoritative information and strategies for the manufacturing sector. The case studies, factories, and individuals featured in these pages (such as "Rajesh in Pune" or "Meera in Chennai" ) are composite accounts based on real-world consulting experiences. Specific names, locations, and identifying business metrics have been altered to protect client confidentiality and proprietary operations.\nThis publication is sold with the understanding that the author is not engaged in rendering legal, accounting, or other professional compliance services. If expert assistance is required, the services of a competent professional should be sought.\nPublished in India.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `READ THIS BEFORE YOU TURN ANOTHER PAGE.` },
      { type: "p", text: `If you are holding this book, you are likely a brilliant engineer or a deeply committed founder who built a manufacturing business from the ground up . You have invested in precise machines, built a loyal workforce, and maintain excellent quality .\nBut right now, you might also be utterly exhausted.\nDespite your 18-hour days and constant operational improvements, your revenue has likely hit a stubborn plateau . You are surviving on volume, but you are not growing in value. You find yourself trapped in a daily knife fight over a few paise, trading rupees with corporate buyers who view you as completely replaceable .\nThis book is going to challenge everything you believe about how to grow a manufacturing company.\nIn the following pages, you will discover:` },
      { type: "ul", items: [
        `The Invisibility Problem: Why doing a little bit of everything for everyone ensures that your company is famous for absolutely nothing .`,
        `The Spreadsheet Reality: How modern procurement strips away your unique value and reduces your life's work to a single row on an Excel spreadsheet, where orders automatically go to the lowest bidder .`,
        `The Quality Illusion: The brutal truth that your world-class quality and on-time delivery are not strategic advantages . They are simply "Operating Imperatives"—the bare minimum required just to be invited to quote .`,
