      { type: "h2", text: `Part 3: What Brand Really Means in Manufacturing` },
      { type: "p", text: `Illustration 6: The B2B Buying Brain (For Chapter 5)\nVisual: A weighing scale.\nDesign: On one side of the scale is a box labelled "Price." On the heavier side, tipping the scale entirely, is a massive anvil labelled "Risk of Failure (Getting Fired)."\nCaption: In consumer markets, buyers look for status. In industrial markets, buyers look for risk mitigation.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Illustration 7: "The Dip" (For Chapter 6)\nVisual: A dual-line graph showing the painful transition of focusing.\nDesign: The first line (Revenue) takes a sharp, terrifying dip downward before slowly climbing back up. The second line (Profit Margin) starts low, but immediately begins climbing upward as the bad revenue is cut.\nCaption: Firing bad clients causes a temporary dip in revenue, but an immediate spike in sanity and pricing power.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `Part 4: The Strategic Awakening` },
      { type: "p", text: `Illustration 8: The Rainmaker Myth (For Chapter 7)\nVisual: A humorous but painful icon graphic.\nDesign: A sleek, high-tech Formula 1 steering wheel attached to a rusted, clunky farm tractor.\nCaption: Hiring an expensive VP of Sales to sell an unfocused, commoditised business is like putting an F1 driver in a tractor. The driver isn't the problem.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Illustration 9: The Strategic Intersection (For Chapter 8)\nVisual: A classic Venn diagram with two overlapping circles.\nLeft Circle: "Where to Play" (Market Opportunity).\nRight Circle: "How to Win" (Uncopyable Capability).\nCenter Overlap: The overlapping section should be shaded dark and labelled "True Brand Power."\nCaption: Choosing a market without a capability is a fantasy. Building a capability without a market is bankruptcy. Strategy is the overlap.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Image 10: The Sea of Sameness (For the Introduction)\nVisual Concept: A sprawling, isometric view of an industrial estate. There are dozens of identical factory sheds with identical smoke stacks. In the middle is one factory glowing or highlighted in a distinct color, representing the "Brand."\nCaption: Hard work makes you busy. A lack of strategy makes you invisible in a sea of capable competitors.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Image 11: The Desk of Chaos (For Chapter 1: The 18-Hour Founder)\nVisual Concept: A photograph or stylized illustration of a founder's desk completely buried under a mountain of blueprints, raw material invoices, and RFQs. A line of employees is standing at the door waiting for approval, while the phone rings off the hook.\nCaption: If every decision has to cross your desk, your business has a hard ceiling on its growth.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Image 12: The Capex Illusion (For Chapter 2: The Efficiency Trap)\nVisual Concept: A hyper-modern, multi-million-rupee 5-axis CNC machine wrapped in a giant red gift bow, with a massive bank loan document sitting next to it.\nCaption: If anyone with a bank loan can buy your competitive advantage, it is not an advantage. It is just expensive overhead.` },
      { type: "p", text: `Image 13: The Spreadsheet Reality (For Chapter 4: The Commodity Trap)\nVisual Concept: A stark, zoomed-in view of an Excel spreadsheet. Row 14 simply says "Supplier A - ₹12.50." Row 15 says "Supplier B - ₹12.00." A red circle is drawn around the ₹12.00 price. All the history, quality, and legacy of the business are nowhere to be seen.\nCaption: To a corporate buyer with no clear differentiator, your life's work is just a row on a spreadsheet.` },
