    blocks: [
      { type: "h1", text: `Appendix C\nThe Strategy Glossary` },
      { type: "p", text: `To change how your company operates, you and your leadership team must change how you speak. Introduce these terms into your boardroom to instantly shift the focus from operational survival to strategic design.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The 18-Hour Founder (The Hero Trap):` },
      { type: "p", text: `A business structure where growth is entirely bottlenecked by the founder’s personal involvement, leading to exhaustion and a hard cap on revenue scale.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The Peanut Butter Business:` },
      { type: "p", text: `A company that spreads its resources, engineering talent, and machine hours too thinly across dozens of unrelated industries, resulting in high operational chaos and zero market distinction.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The Commodity Trap:` },
      { type: "p", text: `The highly vulnerable state of competing purely on price and delivery time because the market views your capabilities as completely interchangeable with your competitors.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `Operating Imperative:` },
      { type: "p", text: `The minimum standard required just to be invited to quote (e.g., good quality, on-time delivery, ISO certification). These are necessary to survive, but they are not strategic advantages.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `Strategic Advantage:` },
      { type: "p", text: `A specific, hard-to-copy capability that makes your company the undeniable, obvious choice for a specific type of buyer, allowing you to command premium pricing.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The Lock & Load Error (Pervasive Sequencing Error):` },
      { type: "p", text: `The fatal mistake of choosing a market niche ("Where to Play") without simultaneously figuring out a unique capability to dominate it ("How to Win").` },
      { type: "h2", text: `The Evidence Trap:` },
      { type: "p", text: `The dangerous boardroom habit of demanding past data to prove that a future strategy will work. This trap limits companies to safe, commoditised ideas.` },
      { type: "h2", text: `What Would Have to Be True? (WWHTBT):` },
